---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import {
  aggregatorRows,
  localRuntimeRows,
  openAiCompatibleRows,
  providerRows
} from "../../facts";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Providers · Squeezy"
  description="Squeezy provider adapter support and local provider configuration."
  activeDoc="/docs/providers/"
  eyebrow="providers"
  heading="Bring your model through one local agent loop."
  lead="Squeezy keeps code analysis, permissions, tool shaping, and session accounting local while routing model turns through configured hosted or local providers."
>
  <section class="doc-block">
    <h2>Aggregators (one key, many models)</h2>
    <p>Quickest start: a single API key (or cloud credential) routes to every frontier model. OpenRouter, Vercel AI Gateway, and PortKey speak the OpenAI-compatible Chat Completions API. Amazon Bedrock is AWS's multi-vendor catalog (Anthropic, Meta, Mistral, Amazon, Cohere, AI21, Stability) over the AWS default credential chain.</p>
    <div class="matrix compact-matrix">
      {
        aggregatorRows.map((row) => (
          <article class="matrix-row">
            <h3>{row.name}</h3>
            <p>{row.detail}</p>
            {row.status && <span class="status-pill">{row.status}</span>}
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-block">
    <h2>First-party vendor APIs</h2>
    <p>Single-vendor endpoints. Each has its own protocol — OpenAI Responses, Anthropic Messages, Gemini streamGenerateContent — and is wired up by a dedicated adapter. Azure OpenAI is Microsoft's hosted OpenAI deployment (OpenAI models only). For Azure AI Foundry's broader catalog (Llama, Phi, Mistral, Cohere, …) use the <code>openai_compatible</code> preset below with the Foundry serverless endpoint as <code>base_url</code>.</p>
    <div class="matrix compact-matrix">
      {
        providerRows.map((row) => (
          <article class="matrix-row">
            <h3>{row.name}</h3>
            <p>{row.detail}</p>
            {row.status && <span class="status-pill">{row.status}</span>}
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-block">
    <h2>Local runtime</h2>
    <p>Run models on the same host as Squeezy. No external network call, no billing, full control over which models are available.</p>
    <div class="matrix compact-matrix">
      {
        localRuntimeRows.map((row) => (
          <article class="matrix-row">
            <h3>{row.name}</h3>
            <p>{row.detail}</p>
            {row.status && <span class="status-pill">{row.status}</span>}
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-block">
    <h2>Other OpenAI-compatible</h2>
    <p>Single-vendor services that speak <code>POST /chat/completions</code> with a Bearer token. The same adapter that drives the aggregators powers these — set the preset, supply an API key, done. The "Custom" preset accepts any base_url so self-hosted proxies (LiteLLM, Cloudflare Workers AI) work too.</p>
    <div class="matrix compact-matrix">
      {
        openAiCompatibleRows.map((row) => (
          <article class="matrix-row">
            <h3>{row.name}</h3>
            <p>{row.detail}</p>
            {row.status && <span class="status-pill">{row.status}</span>}
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
    <p class="footnote">Default models and context windows are seed metadata for routing and local accounting, not provider billing authority.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-block">
    <h2>Configuration</h2>
    <p>Provider settings resolve from CLI flags, environment variables, project config, user settings, and built-in defaults. Aggregators and OpenAI-compatible services use a Bearer API key; first-party vendors use their own header conventions; Bedrock uses the AWS default credential chain; Ollama uses the local runtime.</p>
    <pre><code>[model]
provider = "openrouter"
profile = "balanced"
model = ""

[providers.openrouter]
api_key_env = "OPENROUTER_API_KEY"
default_model = "anthropic/claude-opus-4-7"</code></pre>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
